<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-05-04T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-05-04T19:00:00-05:00" n="548" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d548">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (M)/6125: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>)</head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-05-04T20:00:00-04:00">May 4, 1942—8
                                p.m.</date>
                        </dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>354. Your mail despatch No. 330 March 24<note n="17a" xml:id="d548fn1">Not
                            printed.</note> reports 3305 tons tungsten tin and mercury and 500 tons
                        wood oil ready for shipment at points in Burma. Has Dr. Wong been able to
                        effect transport of these stocks to Myitkyina or to other places of safety
                        and if not what is the likelihood of saving such portion of them as have not
                        been yet lost through Japanese advance? Please report any available
                        information.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>